1/**
2 @file upmf.c
3
4 @brief Functions for manipulating EMF+ files and structures.
5
6 EMF+ is much more object based than is EMF or WMF, so the U_PMR_*_set and most U_PMF_*_set functions
7 return a pointer to a PseudoObject. PseudoObjects are structs that contain a data field to hold the
8 object in EMF+ file byte order, size information, and some type information. This is sufficient to allow
9 complex records to be built up from the various sorts of nested objects which they normally contain.
10 If something goes wrong a NULL pointer is returned and recsize is set to 0.
11
12 EMF+ does not use a separate set of endian functions, _get and _set routines convert from/to
13 the EMF+ file byte order on the fly.
14
15 WARNING: Microsoft's EMF+ documentation is little-endian for everything EXCEPT
16 bitfields, which are big-endian. See EMF+ manual section 1.3.2
17 That documentation also uses 0 as the MOST significant bit, N-1 as the least.
18 This code is little-endian throughout, and 0 is the LEAST significant bit
19
20*/
21
22/*
23File: upmf.c

25Date: 21-MAR-2019
26Author: David Mathog, Biology Division, Caltech
27email: mathog@caltech.edu

29*/

71/**
72 \brief Utility function for writing one or more EMF+ records in a PseudoObject to the EMF output file
73 \return 1 on success, 0 on error.
74 \param po U_PSEUDO_OBJ to write, it is deleted after it is written
75 \param sum U_PSEUDO_OBJ to use for scratch space
76 \param et EMFTRACK used to write records to EMF file
77*/
78int U_PMR_write(U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po, U_PSEUDO_OBJ *sum, EMFTRACK *et){
79 char *rec;
80 int status = 0;
81 sum->Used = 0; /* clean it out, retaining allocated memory */
82 sum = U_PO_append(sum, "EMF+", 4); /* indicates that this comment holds an EMF+ record */
83 if(!sum)goto end;
84 sum = U_PO_append(sum, po->Data, po->Used); /* the EMF+ record itself */
85 if(!sum)goto end;
86 U_PO_free(&po); /* delete the PseudoObject */
87 rec = U_EMRCOMMENT_set(sum->Used, sum->Data); /* stuff it into the EMF comment */
88 if(!emf_append((PU_ENHMETARECORD)rec, et, 1))goto end; /* write it to the EMF file, delete the record, check status */
89 status = 1;
90end:
91 return(status);
92}
93
94/**
95 \brief Utility function to draw a line.
96 \return 1 on success, 0 on error.
97 \param PenID Index of U_PMF_PEN object to use in the EMF+ object table (0-63, inclusive)
98 \param PathID Index of U_PMF_PATH object to use in the EMF+ object table (0-63, inclusive)
99 \param Start U_PMF_POINTF coordinates of start of line.
100 \param End U_PMF_POINTF coordinates of end of line.
101 \param Dashed Set if the line is dashed, clear if it is not.
102 \param sum PseudoObject used for scratch space
103 \param et EMFTRACK used to write records to EMF file
104
105*/
106int U_PMR_drawline(uint32_t PenID, uint32_t PathID, U_PMF_POINTF Start, U_PMF_POINTF End, int Dashed, U_PSEUDO_OBJ *sum, EMFTRACK *et){
107 U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *dpath;
108 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *poPath;
109 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po;
110 int status=0;
111 int PTP_value = ( Dashed ? U_PTP_DashMode0x10 : U_PTP_None0x00);
112 dpath = U_PATH_create(0, NULL((void*)0), 0, 0); /* create an empty path*/
113 if(dpath){
114 if(U_PATH_moveto(dpath, Start, PTP_value) && U_PATH_lineto(dpath, End, PTP_value)){
115 poPath = U_PMF_PATH_set2(U_PMF_GRAPHICSVERSIONOBJ_set(2), dpath);
116 if(poPath){
117 po = U_PMR_OBJECT_PO_set(PathID, poPath);
118 U_PO_free(&poPath);
119 if(po){
120 U_PMR_write(po, sum, et);
121 po = U_PMR_DRAWPATH_set(PathID, PenID);
122 if(po){
123 U_PMR_write(po, sum, et);
124 status = 1;
125 }
126 }
127 }
128 }
129 U_DPO_free(&dpath);
130 }
131 return(status);
132}

134/**
135 \brief Utility function for drawing strings onto the baseline in one call.
136 \return 1 on success, 0 on error.
137 \param string Text to draw in UTF-8 format
138 \param Vpos StringAlignment Enumeration. Always drawn on baseline, but using one of these three modes.
139 \param FontID Index of U_PMF_FONT object to use in the EMF+ object table (0-63, inclusive)
140 \param BrushID U_PSEUDO_OBJ containing a U_PMF_ARGB or a U_PMF_4NUM. Color or U_PMF_BRUSH object in the EMF+ object table (0-63, inclusive)
141 \param FormatID index of U_PMF_STRINGFORMAT object to use in the EMF+ Object Table.
142 \param Sfs StringFormat structure. Ignored values: StringAlignment, LineAlign, Flags
143 \param FontName Name of font to draw with
144 \param Height Height of font in pixels (positive)
145 \param fip U_FontInfoParams (ascent, descent, and so forth)
146 \param FontFlags FontStyle Flags
147 \param x X position in pixels of left side of EM box of first character
148 \param y Y position in pixels of baseline of first character
149 \param sum PseudoObject used for scratch space
150 \param et EMFTRACK used to write records to EMF file
151
152 EMF+ manual 2.3.4.14, Microsoft name: EmfPlusDrawString Record, Index 0x1C
153
154 For most fonts Ascent and Descent are used to adjust the bounding box to properly position the
155 baseline. Some fonts, like Verdana, are strange and they position the baseline on the bottom of
156 the bounding box if that box has the same height as the font. For those fonts specify 0.0 for
157 both Ascent and Descent.
158*/
159int U_PMR_drawstring( const char *string, int Vpos, uint32_t FontID, const U_PSEUDO_OBJ *BrushID, uint32_t FormatID,
160 U_PMF_STRINGFORMAT Sfs, const char *FontName, U_FLOAT Height, U_FontInfoParams *fip, uint32_t FontFlags,
161 U_FLOAT x, U_FLOAT y, U_PSEUDO_OBJ *sum, EMFTRACK *et){
162 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po;
163 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *poSF;
164 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *poFont;
165 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *poRect;
166 U_FLOAT rx,ry,rw,rh,rd;
167 uint16_t *UFontName;
168 uint16_t *Text16;
169 int slen;
170 int status = 0;
171 double aval, dval;
172
173 Sfs.Flags = U_SF_NoFitBlackBox0x00000004 + U_SF_NoClip0x00004000;
174
175 if(Vpos < U_SA_Near0x00 || Vpos > U_SA_Far0x02)return(0);
176 Sfs.StringAlignment = U_SA_Near0x00; // Horizontal
177 Sfs.LineAlign = Vpos; // Vertical
178
179 UFontName = U_Utf8ToUtf16le(FontName, 0, NULL((void*)0));
180 slen = strlen(FontName);
181 poFont = U_PMF_FONT_set(U_PMF_GRAPHICSVERSIONOBJ_set(2), Height, U_UT_World0x00, FontFlags, slen, UFontName);
182 if(poFont){
183 po = U_PMR_OBJECT_PO_set(FontID, poFont); /* font to use */
184 if(po){
185 U_PMR_write(po, sum, et);
186
187 poSF = U_PMF_STRINGFORMAT_set(&Sfs, NULL((void*)0));
188 if(poSF){
189 po = U_PMR_OBJECT_PO_set(FormatID, poSF);
190 U_PO_free(&poSF);
191 if(po){
192 U_PMR_write(po, sum, et);
193
194 rw = 4*Height*slen; /* This could probably be any value */
195 rh = Height;
196 rx = x;
197 if(fip->LineGap > -fip->Descent){ aval = fip->yMax; } // sylfaen, palatino
198 else { aval = fip->Ascent; } // others
199 if(fip->LineGap && (fip->LineGap < -fip->Descent)){ dval = ((double) (fip->Descent - fip->LineGap)) / ((double) fip->EmSize); } //shruti and some others
200 else { dval = ((double) fip->Descent ) / ((double) fip->EmSize); }
201 switch(Vpos){
202 case U_SA_Near0x00:
203 rd = Height * aval / ((double) fip->EmSize);
204 break;
205 case U_SA_Center0x01:
206 rd = 0.5 * ( Height * aval / ((double) fip->EmSize) + Height * ( 1.0 + dval));
207 break;
208 case U_SA_Far0x02:
209 rd = Height * ( 1.0 + dval);
210 break;
211 }
212 ry = y - rd; /* draw from upper left corner, which is shifted to put baseline on y */
213 poRect = U_PMF_RECTF4_set(rx, ry, rw, rh);
214#if 0
215(void) U_PMR_drawline(OBJ_PEN_BLACK_1,OBJ_PATH_1, (U_PMF_POINTF){x-100, ry}, (U_PMF_POINTF){x+100, ry}, 0, sum, et);
216(void) U_PMR_drawline(OBJ_PEN_BLACK_1,OBJ_PATH_1, (U_PMF_POINTF){x-100, ry+rh}, (U_PMF_POINTF){x+100, ry+rh}, 0, sum, et);
217(void) U_PMR_drawline(OBJ_PEN_BLACK_1,OBJ_PATH_1, (U_PMF_POINTF){x-100, ry}, (U_PMF_POINTF){x-100, ry + Height * (double) fip->Ascent / ((double) fip->EmSize)}, 0, sum, et);
218(void) U_PMR_drawline(OBJ_PEN_BLACK_1,OBJ_PATH_1, (U_PMF_POINTF){x- 90, ry}, (U_PMF_POINTF){x- 90, ry - Height * (double) fip->Descent / ((double) fip->EmSize)}, 0, sum, et);
219(void) U_PMR_drawline(OBJ_PEN_BLACK_1,OBJ_PATH_1, (U_PMF_POINTF){x- 80, ry}, (U_PMF_POINTF){x- 80, ry + Height * (double) fip->yMax / ((double) fip->EmSize)}, 0, sum, et);
220(void) U_PMR_drawline(OBJ_PEN_BLACK_1,OBJ_PATH_1, (U_PMF_POINTF){x- 70, ry}, (U_PMF_POINTF){x- 70, ry - Height * (double) fip->yMin / ((double) fip->EmSize)}, 0, sum, et);
221(void) U_PMR_drawline(OBJ_PEN_BLACK_1,OBJ_PATH_1, (U_PMF_POINTF){x- 60, ry}, (U_PMF_POINTF){x- 60, ry + Height * (double) fip->LineGap / ((double) fip->EmSize)}, 0, sum, et);
222(void) U_PMR_drawline(OBJ_PEN_BLACK_1,OBJ_PATH_1, (U_PMF_POINTF){x- 50, ry}, (U_PMF_POINTF){x- 50, ry + Height * ( 1.0 - (((double) (fip->LineGap - fip->Descent)) / ((double) fip->EmSize)) )}, 0, sum, et);
223#endif
224
225 Text16 = U_Utf8ToUtf16le(string, 0, NULL((void*)0));
226 slen = strlen(string);
227 po = U_PMR_DRAWSTRING_set(FontID, BrushID, FormatID, slen, poRect, Text16);
228 if(po){
229 U_PMR_write(po, sum, et);
230 status = 1; /* Success!!! */
231 }
232 U_PO_free(&poRect);
233 free(Text16);
234 }
235 }
236 }
237 U_PO_free(&poFont);
238 }
239 free(UFontName);
240 return(status);
241}

243/**
244 \brief Allocate and construct an array of U_POINT16 objects from a set of U_PMF_POINTF objects, endianness in and out is LE
245 \returns pointer to an array of U_POINT16 structures.
246 \param points pointer to the source U_POINT structures
247 \param count number of members in points
248
249 If a coordinate is out of range it saturates at boundary.
250*/
251U_PMF_POINT *POINTF_To_POINT16_LE(U_PMF_POINTF *points, int count){
252 U_PMF_POINT *newpts;
253 U_PMF_POINTF ptfl;
254 int i;
255 newpts = (U_PMF_POINT *) malloc(count * sizeof(U_PMF_POINT));
256
257 for(i=0; i<count; i++){
258 memcpy(&ptfl, &(points[i]), 8);
259 if(U_BYTE_SWAP0){ U_swap4(&ptfl,2); } /* on BE platforms swap going in and coming out */
260 newpts[i].X = U_MNMX(ptfl.X, INT16_MIN, INT16_MAX)((ptfl.X)<((-32767-1))?((-32767-1)):((ptfl.X)>((32767))
?((32767)):(ptfl.X)));
261 newpts[i].Y = U_MNMX(ptfl.Y, INT16_MIN, INT16_MAX)((ptfl.Y)<((-32767-1))?((-32767-1)):((ptfl.Y)>((32767))
?((32767)):(ptfl.Y)));
262 if(U_BYTE_SWAP0){ U_swap2(&(newpts[i]),2); }
263 }
264 return(newpts);
265}

340/**
341 \brief Convert from PseudoObject OID to ObjectType enumeration.
342 \returns OT value on success, 0 if no match
343 \param OID PseudoObject OID (based on EMF+ manual chapter number. )
344
345 Only OTs that may be stored in the EMF+ object table are supported.
346*/
347
348int U_OID_To_OT(uint32_t OID){
349 int otype;
350 if( OID==U_PMF_BRUSH_OID0x02020101 ){ otype = U_OT_Brush0x01; }
351 else if(OID==U_PMF_PEN_OID0x02020107 ){ otype = U_OT_Pen0x02; }
352 else if(OID==U_PMF_PATH_OID0x02020106 ){ otype = U_OT_Path0x03; }
353 else if(OID==U_PMF_REGION_OID0x02020108 ){ otype = U_OT_Region0x04; }
354 else if(OID==U_PMF_IMAGE_OID0x02020104 ){ otype = U_OT_Image0x05; }
355 else if(OID==U_PMF_FONT_OID0x02020103 ){ otype = U_OT_Font0x06; }
356 else if(OID==U_PMF_STRINGFORMAT_OID0x02020109 ){ otype = U_OT_StringFormat0x07; }
357 else if(OID==U_PMF_IMAGEATTRIBUTES_OID0x02020105){ otype = U_OT_ImageAttributes0x08; }
358 else if(OID==U_PMF_CUSTOMLINECAP_OID0x02020102 ){ otype = U_OT_CustomLineCap0x09; }
359 else { otype = U_OT_Invalid0x00; }
360 return(otype);
361}
362
363/**
364 \brief Convert from PseudoObject OID to BrushType enumeration.
365 \returns BT value on success, -1 if no match
366 \param OID PseudoObject OID (based on EMF+ manual chapter number. )
367
368 Only OIDs that map to BT's are supported.
369*/
370
371int U_OID_To_BT(uint32_t OID){
372 int otype;
373 if( OID==U_PMF_HATCHBRUSHDATA_OID0x02020220 ){ otype = U_BT_HatchFill0x01; }
374 else if(OID==U_PMF_LINEARGRADIENTBRUSHDATA_OID0x02020224 ){ otype = U_BT_LinearGradient0x04; }
375 else if(OID==U_PMF_PATHGRADIENTBRUSHDATA_OID0x02020229 ){ otype = U_BT_PathGradient0x03; }
376 else if(OID==U_PMF_SOLIDBRUSHDATA_OID0x02020243 ){ otype = U_BT_SolidColor0x00; }
377 else if(OID==U_PMF_TEXTUREBRUSHDATA_OID0x02020245 ){ otype = U_BT_TextureFill0x02; }
378 else { otype = -1; }
379 return(otype);
380}
381
382/**
383 \brief Convert from PseudoObject OID to CustomLineCapDataType Enumeration.
384 \returns BT value on success, -1 if no match
385 \param OID PseudoObject OID (based on EMF+ manual chapter number. )
386
387 Only OIDs that map to CLCDT's are supported.
388*/
389
390int U_OID_To_CLCDT(uint32_t OID){
391 int otype;
392 if( OID==U_PMF_CUSTOMLINECAPDATA_OID0x02020213 ){ otype = U_CLCDT_Default0x00; }
393 else if(OID==U_PMF_CUSTOMLINECAPARROWDATA_OID0x02020212 ){ otype = U_CLCDT_AdjustableArrow0x01; }
394 else { otype = -1; }
395 return(otype);
396}
397
398/**
399 \brief Convert from PseudoObject OID to ImageDataType Enumeration.
400 \returns BT value on success, -1 if no match
401 \param OID PseudoObject OID (based on EMF+ manual chapter number. )
402
403 Only OIDs that map to IDT's are supported.
404*/
405
406int U_OID_To_IDT(uint32_t OID){
407 int otype;
408 if( OID==U_PMF_BITMAP_OID0x02020202 ){ otype = U_IDT_Bitmap0x01; }
409 else if(OID==U_PMF_METAFILE_OID0x02020227 ){ otype = U_IDT_Metafile0x02; }
410 else { otype = -1; }
411 return(otype);
412}
413
414/**
415 \brief Convert from PseudoObject OID to RegionNodeDataType Enumeration.
416 \returns BT value on success, -1 if no match
417 \param OID PseudoObject OID (based on EMF+ manual chapter number. )
418
419 Only OIDs that map to RNDT's are supported.
420*/
421
422int U_OID_To_RNDT(uint32_t OID){
423 int otype;
424 if( OID==U_PMF_REGIONNODECHILDNODES_OID0x02020241 ){ otype = U_RNDT_Kids0x00000000; } /* there are 5 types, which must be specified separately */
425 else if(OID==U_PMF_RECTF_OID0x02020239 ){ otype = U_RNDT_Rect0x10000000; }
426 else if(OID==U_PMF_REGIONNODEPATH_OID0x02020242 ){ otype = U_RNDT_Path0x10000001; }
427 else { otype = -1; }
428 return(otype);
429}
430
431/**
432 \brief Append data to an U_OBJ_ACCUM structure.
433 \param oa pointer to the U_OBJ_ACCUM structure
434 \param data data to add
435 \param size bytes in data
436 \param Type object type
437 \param Id Object ID
438 \returns 0 on success, !0 on error. -1 on Type change, -2 on Id change
439
440 Safe to test for Id, Type changes by calling with size=0.
441*/
442int U_OA_append(U_OBJ_ACCUM *oa, const char *data, int size, int Type, int Id){
443 int tail;
444 if(!oa)return(2);
445 if(oa->used){
446 if(oa->Type != Type)return(-1);
447 if(oa->Id != Id)return(-2);
448 }
449 tail = oa->used;
450 if(oa->used + size >= oa->space){
451 oa->space += size;
452 char *newaccum = (char *) realloc(oa->accum, oa->space);
453 if(!newaccum){
454 oa->space -= size; /* put it back the way it was */
455 return(1);
456 }
457 oa->accum = newaccum;
458 }
459 memcpy(oa->accum + tail,data,size);
460 oa->used += size;
461 oa->Type = Type;
462 oa->Id = Id;
463 return(0);
464}
465
466
467/**
468 \brief Clear an U_OBJ_ACCUM structure. Accumulated storage is retained.
469 \param oa pointer to the U_OBJ_ACCUM structure
470 \returns 0 on success, !0 on error.
471*/
472int U_OA_clear(U_OBJ_ACCUM *oa){
473 if(!oa)return(2);
474 oa->used=0;
475 /* Type and Id may be ignored as they are reset on the first append */
476 return(0);
477}
478
479/**
480 \brief Release an U_OBJ_ACCUM structure. Accumulated storage is free'd.
481 \param oa pointer to the U_OBJ_ACCUM structure
482 \returns 0 on success, !0 on error.
483*/
484int U_OA_release(U_OBJ_ACCUM *oa){
485 if(!oa)return(2);
486 oa->used=0;
487 oa->space = 0;
488 if(oa->accum)free(oa->accum);
489 oa->accum=NULL((void*)0);
490 return(0);
491}
492
493/**
494 \brief Create and set an U_PSEUDO_OBJ
495 \returns pointer to the U_PSEUDO_OBJ, NULL on error
496 \param Data Data to copy into the PseudoObject's data. If NULL, space is allocated, but is cleared instead of filled.
497 \param Size Number of bytes to allocate for Data (may be >Use if padding is present)
498 \param Use Number of data bytes in Data (whether or not Data is actually copied)
499 \param Type Type numbers are from manual section: 1.2.3.47 -> 0x01020347
500
501 If Data is NULL and Size is 0 an empty PseudoObject is created. One byte of storage
502 is allocated for Data, Size is set to 1, and Used to 0.
503
504 If Data is NULL and Size is !0 a zero filled PseudoObject is created.
505
506 If Data is !Null and Size is !0 a data filled PseudoObject is created.
507*/
508U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PO_create(char *Data, size_t Size, size_t Use, uint32_t Type){
509 if(Use>Size)return(NULL((void*)0));
510 size_t tSize = (Size ? Size : 1);
511 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = (U_PSEUDO_OBJ *)malloc(sizeof(U_PSEUDO_OBJ));
512 if(po){
513 po->Data = malloc(tSize);
514 if(po->Data){
515 po->Size = tSize;
516 po->Used = Use;
517 po->Type = Type;
518 if(Data){ memcpy(po->Data, Data, Use); } /* if Use < Size uninitialized bytes will be present! */
519 else { memset(po->Data, 0, tSize); }
520 }
521 else {
522 free(po);
523 po=NULL((void*)0);
524 }
525 }
526 return(po);
527}
528
529/**
530 \brief Append data to a U_PSEUDO_OBJ object and return it
531 \returns pointer to the U_PSEUDO_OBJ object, NULL on error
532 \param po PseudoObject to append to. Cannot be NULL.
533 \param Data Data to copy into the PseudoObject's data. If NULL, space is allocated (if necessary) and cleared instead of filled.
534 \param Size Number of data bytes in Data
535*/
536U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PO_append(U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po, const char *Data, size_t Size){
537 /* po cannot be NULL,as in U_PO_po_append(), because there would be no way to determine the TYPE of the resulting PO */
538 if(po){
539 if(!po->Data || po->Used + Size > po->Size){
540 po->Size = po->Used + Size;
541 char *newData = realloc(po->Data, po->Size);
542 if(!newData){
543 po->Size -= Size; /* put it back the way it was*/
544 po=NULL((void*)0); /* skip the rest of the actions, does not affect po in caller */
545 }
546 else {
547 po->Data = newData;
548 }
549 }
550 if(po){ /* po->Data ready to append new data */
551 if(Data){ memcpy(po->Data + po->Used, Data, Size); }
552 else { memset(po->Data + po->Used, 0, Size); }
553 po->Used += Size;
554 }
555 }
556 return(po);
557}
558
559/**
560 \brief Append data to a U_PSEUDO_OBJ object and return it
561 \returns pointer to the U_PSEUDO_OBJ object, NULL on error
562 \param po PseudoObject to append to. May be NULL.
563 \param Src PseudoObject to append.
564 \param StripE Set: leading Elements in Src->Data is not copied, Clear: it is copied.
565*/
566U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PO_po_append(U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po, U_PSEUDO_OBJ *Src, int StripE){
567 if(!Src){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
568 if((StripE && (Src->Used == 4)) || !Src->Used){ return(po); } /* appending nothing is not an error */
569 char *Data = Src->Data;
570 size_t Size = Src->Used; /* append only what is used */
571 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *ipo = po;
572 if(StripE){ Size -= 4; }
573 if(!ipo){
574 ipo = U_PO_create(NULL((void*)0), 0, 0, Src->Type); /* create an empty pseudoobject */
575 }
576 if(ipo){
577 if(!ipo->Data || ipo->Used + Size > ipo->Size){
578 ipo->Size = ipo->Used + Size;
579 char *newData = realloc(ipo->Data, ipo->Size);
580 if(!newData){
581 if(ipo != po)U_PO_free(&ipo);
582 }
583 else {
584 ipo->Data = newData;
585 }
586 }
587 if(ipo){
588 if(Data){
589 if(StripE){ memcpy(ipo->Data + ipo->Used, Data + 4, Size); } /* Size is already 4 less, skip the leading Elements value */
590 else { memcpy(ipo->Data + ipo->Used, Data, Size); } /* copy everything */
591 }
592 else { memset(ipo->Data + ipo->Used, 0, Size); } /* set everything */
593 ipo->Used += Size;
594 }
595 }
596 return(ipo);
597}
598
599/**
600 \brief Free an U_PSEUDO_OBJ structure. All associated memory is released.
601 \param po Address of a pointer to the U_PSEUDO_OBJ structure, Pointer is set to NULL.
602 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
603*/
604int U_PO_free(U_PSEUDO_OBJ **po){
605 if(!po)return(0);
606 if(!*po)return(1);
607 if((*po)->Data)free((*po)->Data);
608 free(*po);
609 *po=NULL((void*)0);
610 return(1);
611}
612
613/** \brief create a PseudoObject with data in the correct byte order for an EMF+ file.
614 \returns The PseudoObject on success, NULL on error.
615
616 \param Type the type of the PseudoObject that is created. Allowed values are in U_PID_Values.
617 \param List an array of U_SERIAL_DESC structures containing the data to store.
618
619 The U_PMF_SERIAL_set() function should not ever be called directly by end user code.
620
621 Each U_SERIAL_DESC element in List consists of Data fields and a description of that data. List is terminated
622 by the first U_SERIAL_DESC element having a TE value of U_XX.
623
624 Data fields: an array of a basic type of Units bytes repeated Reps times with the target byte order
625 described in TE.
626
627 Ptrs: Address of the first byte of the data fields.
628
629 Units: Number of bytes of in each data field unit
630
631 Reps: Number of repeats of the unit in data fields.
632 If a Ptr is NULL, and Units*Reps is not zero, then Units*Reps 0x00 bytes are stored.
633 If a Ptr is NULL, and Units*Reps is zero, this U_SERIAL_DESC is ignored.
634 if a Ptr is NOT NULL, and Units * Reps is not zero, then the data is stored in the indicated byte order.
635 If a Ptr is NOT NULL, and Units or Reps is zero an error is signaled.
636
637 TE: (Target Endian) the byte order in which to store each unit of a data field as defined in U_Endian.
638 Byte swapping is only enabled when Units is 2 or 4. In addition to the byte order values U_XE, U_LE,
639 and U_BE, and the array terminator U_XX, the value may also be U_RP. U_RP means there is only a
640 single unit in the data fields, but it is to be copied to the target Reps times. That is, the data
641 was passed in with a form of run length encoding.
642
643 Creates an empty PseudoObject if all pointers are NULL and all sizes are zero.
644 */
645U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_SERIAL_set(uint32_t Type, const U_SERIAL_DESC *List){
646 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po=NULL((void*)0);
647 size_t Total=0;
648 size_t FSize;
649 char *cptr;
650 char *hptr;
651 const U_SERIAL_DESC *lptr;
652 if(!List)return(NULL((void*)0));
653 for(lptr=List; lptr->TE != U_XX0xFF; lptr++){
654 FSize = lptr->Units * lptr->Reps;
655 if(!FSize && lptr->Ptr)return(po);
656 Total += FSize;
657 }
658 po = U_PO_create(NULL((void*)0), Total, Total, Type);
659 if(po){
660 cptr = po->Data;
661 for(lptr=List; lptr->TE != U_XX0xFF; lptr++){
662 FSize = lptr->Units * lptr->Reps;
663 if(FSize){ /* Ptr is not NULL, that would have been detected already */
664 hptr = cptr;
665 if(lptr->TE & U_RP4){ U_PMF_REPCPY_DSTSHIFT(&cptr, lptr->Ptr, lptr->Units, lptr->Reps); }
666 else { U_PMF_MEMCPY_DSTSHIFT(&cptr, lptr->Ptr, FSize); }
667 if(((lptr->TE & U_LE1) && U_IS_BE0) || ((lptr->TE & U_BE2) && U_IS_LE1)){
668 if(lptr->Units==2){ U_swap2(hptr,lptr->Reps); }
669 else if(lptr->Units==4){ U_swap4(hptr,lptr->Reps); }
670 }
671 }
672 }
673 }
674 return(po);
675}
676
677/**
678 \brief Create U_DPSEUDO_OBJ's for the Points and Types of a path
679 \param Elements Number of elements in Points. May be zero, which creates an empty path.
680 \param Points Array of U_PMF_POINTF values.
681 \param First Apply to first point, unsigned byte, lower 4 bits hold the PathPointType flag upper 4 bits hold the PathPointType enumeration. Must have U_PPT_Start set.
682 \param Others Apply to all other points, unsigned byte, lower 4 bits hold the PathPointType flag upper 4 bits hold the PathPointType enumeration. Must have U_PPT_Line or U_PPT_Bezier set.
683 \returns pointer to the DU_PSEUDO_OBJ object, NULL on error
684*/
685U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *U_PATH_create(int Elements, const U_PMF_POINTF *Points, uint8_t First, uint8_t Others){
686 if(Elements){
687 if(!Points){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
688 if( (First & U_PPT_MASK0x0F) != U_PPT_Start0x00 ){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
689 if(!(Others & U_PPT_Bezier0x03)){ return(NULL((void*)0)); } /* will pass if either line or bezier is set */
690 }
691
692 U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *Path = (U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *)calloc(sizeof(U_DPSEUDO_OBJ),1); /* make poTypes and poPoints NULL */
693 const U_SERIAL_DESC List[] = { {NULL((void*)0),0,0,U_XX0xFF} };
694 if(Path){
695 Path->Elements = Elements;
696 Path->poPoints = U_PMF_SERIAL_set(U_PMF_RAW_OID0x40000002, List); /* Empty PO to hold points as raw data */
697 if(!Elements){
698 Path->poTypes = U_PMF_SERIAL_set(U_PMF_RAW_OID0x40000002, List); /* Empty PO to hold types as raw data */
699 }
700 else {
701 Path->poPoints = U_PO_append(Path->poPoints, (char *)Points, Elements*sizeof(U_PMF_POINTF));
702 if(Path->poPoints){
703 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *tpo = U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPE_set2(Elements, First | U_PPT_Start0x00, Others); /* PO holding types, has leading Elements value */
704 Path->poTypes = U_PO_po_append(NULL((void*)0), tpo, U_PMF_DROP_ELEMENTS1); /* remove the leading Elements value*/
705 U_PO_free(&tpo);
706 if(!Path->poTypes){ U_PO_free(&Path->poPoints); }
707 }
708 if(!Path->poPoints){ U_DPO_free(&Path); }
709 }
710 }
711 return(Path);
712}
713
714/**
715 \brief Free U_DPSEUDO_OBJ's
716 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
717*/
718int U_DPO_free(U_DPSEUDO_OBJ **dpo){
719 if(!dpo){ return(0); }
720 if(!*dpo){ return(1); }
721 U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *kpo = *dpo;
722 if(kpo->poPoints){ U_PO_free(&kpo->poPoints); }
723 if(kpo->poTypes){ U_PO_free(&kpo->poTypes); }
724 free(*dpo);
725 *dpo=NULL((void*)0);
726 return(1);
727}
728
729/**
730 \brief Clear U_DPSEUDO_OBJ's. Memory is retained, Elements and Used values are set to 0.
731 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
732
733 It is much more efficient to clear a DPO and reuse it than to free that DPO and create another.
734*/
735int U_DPO_clear(U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *dpo){
736 if(!dpo){ return(0); }
737 if(dpo->poPoints){ dpo->poPoints->Used = 0; }
738 if(dpo->poTypes){ dpo->poTypes->Used = 0; }
739 dpo->Elements = 0;
740 return(1);
741}
742
743/**
744 \brief Append a "moveto" point to a path
745 \param Path Address of a DoublePseudoObject holding the path to append to.
746 \param Point Point to move to.
747 \param Flags Flags may be (U_PTP_None, U_PTP_DashMode, U_PTP_PathMarker, U_PTP_NoBit, U_PTP_CloseSubpath)
748 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
749*/
750int U_PATH_moveto(U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *Path, U_PMF_POINTF Point, uint8_t Flags){
751 if(!Path){ return(0); }
752 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *tpo;
753 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *tpo2;
754 uint8_t Type = (Flags & U_PTP_NotClose0x70) | U_PPT_Start0x00;
755
756 tpo = U_PMF_POINTF_set(1, &Point);
757 if(!tpo){ return(0); }
758 tpo2 = U_PO_po_append(Path->poPoints, tpo, U_PMF_DROP_ELEMENTS1);
759 U_PO_free(&tpo);
760 if(!tpo2)return(0);
761 Path->poPoints = tpo2;
762
763
764 tpo = U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPE_set(1, &Type);
765 if(!tpo){ return(0); }
766 tpo2= U_PO_po_append(Path->poTypes, tpo, U_PMF_DROP_ELEMENTS1);
767 U_PO_free(&tpo);
768 if(!tpo2)return(0);
769 Path->poTypes = tpo2;
770
771 Path->Elements++;
772 return(1);
773}
774
775/**
776 \brief Append a "lineto" point to a path
777 \param Path Address of a DoublePseudoObject holding the path to append to.
778 \param Point U_PMF_POINTF point to draw to.
779 \param Flags Flags may be (U_PTP_None, U_PTP_DashMode, U_PTP_PathMarker, U_PTP_NoBit, U_PTP_CloseSubpath)
780 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
781*/
782int U_PATH_lineto(U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *Path, U_PMF_POINTF Point, uint8_t Flags){
783 if(!Path || !Path->Elements){ return(0); } /* must be at least one point to extend from */
784 if(Path->poTypes->Data[Path->Elements - 1] & U_PTP_CloseSubpath0x80){ return(0); } /* cannot extend a closed subpath */
785 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *tpo;
786 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *tpo2;
787 uint8_t Type = (Flags & U_PTP_NotClose0x70) | U_PPT_Line0x01;
788 tpo = U_PMF_POINTF_set(1, &Point);
789 if(!tpo){ return(0); }
790 tpo2 = U_PO_po_append(Path->poPoints, tpo, U_PMF_DROP_ELEMENTS1);
791 U_PO_free(&tpo);
792 if(!tpo2)return(0);
793 Path->poPoints = tpo2;
794
795
796 tpo = U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPE_set(1, &Type);
797 if(!tpo){ return(0); }
798 tpo2 = U_PO_po_append(Path->poTypes, tpo, U_PMF_DROP_ELEMENTS1);
799 U_PO_free(&tpo);
800 if(!tpo2)return(0);
801 Path->poTypes = tpo2;
802
803 Path->Elements++;
804 return(1);
805}
806
807/**
808 \brief Set the closepath bit in the last point
809 \param Path Address of a DoublePseudoObject holding the path to act upon.
810 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
811*/
812int U_PATH_closepath(U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *Path){
813 if(!Path || !Path->poTypes){ return(0); }
814 uint32_t Elements = Path->Elements;
815 uint8_t *Type = (uint8_t *)(Path->poTypes->Data) + Elements - 1;
816 if(*Type & U_PPT_Start0x00){ return(0); } /* single point closed path makes no sense */
817 *Type = *Type | U_PTP_CloseSubpath0x80;
818 return(1);
819}
820
821/**
822 \brief Append a "polylineto" set of point to a path
823 \param Path Address of a DoublePseudoObject holding the path to append to.
824 \param Elements number of Points and Flags
825 \param Points Line points.
826 \param Flags Flags (U_PTP_None, U_PTP_DashMode, U_PTP_PathMarker, U_PTP_NoBit, but NOT U_PTP_CloseSubpath)
827 \param StartSeg If set, use U_PPT_Start PathPointType enumeration for first point, otherwise use U_PPT_Line.
828 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
829*/
830int U_PATH_polylineto(U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *Path, uint32_t Elements, const U_PMF_POINTF *Points, uint8_t Flags, uint8_t StartSeg){
831 if(!Path || !Points){ return(0); }
832 if(!Elements){ return(1); } /* harmless - do nothing */
833 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *tpo;
834 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *tpo2;
835 uint8_t First, Others;
836
837 tpo = U_PMF_POINTF_set(Elements, Points);
838 tpo2 = U_PO_po_append(Path->poPoints, tpo, U_PMF_DROP_ELEMENTS1);
839 U_PO_free(&tpo);
840 if(!tpo2)return(0);
841 Path->poPoints = tpo2;
842
843 if(StartSeg){ First = (Flags & U_PTP_NotClose0x70) | U_PPT_Start0x00; }
844 else { First = (Flags & U_PTP_NotClose0x70) | U_PPT_Line0x01; }
845 Others = (Flags & U_PTP_NotClose0x70) | U_PPT_Line0x01;
846 tpo = U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPE_set2(Elements, First, Others);
847 if(!tpo){ return(0); }
848 tpo2 = U_PO_po_append(Path->poTypes, tpo, U_PMF_DROP_ELEMENTS1);
849 U_PO_free(&tpo);
850 if(!tpo2)return(0);
851 Path->poTypes = tpo2;
852
853 Path->Elements += Elements;
854 return(1);
855}
856
857
858/**
859 \brief Append a "polybezierto" set of point to a path
860 \param Path Address of a DoublePseudoObject holding the path to append to.
861 \param Elements number of Points
862 \param Points Bezier points. Optional starting point, then N sets of 3, example: [P1] (Q12A Q12B P2) (Q23A Q23B P3).
863 \param Flags Flags (U_PTP_None, U_PTP_DashMode, U_PTP_PathMarker, U_PTP_NoBit, but NOT U_PTP_CloseSubpath)
864 \param StartSeg If set, use U_PPT_Start PathPointType enumeration for first point, otherwise use U_PPT_Bezier.
865 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
866
867 If Start is set Elements must be 1 + multiple of 3. Ie, P1 Q12A Q12B P2 Q23A Q23B P3
868
869 If Start is clear Elements must be a multiple of 3. Ie, (P1, already in path) Q12A Q12B P2 Q23A Q23B P3
870*/
871int U_PATH_polybezierto(U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *Path, uint32_t Elements, const U_PMF_POINTF *Points, uint8_t Flags, uint8_t StartSeg){
872 if(!Path || !Points){ return(0); }
873 if(!Elements){
874 if(StartSeg){ return(0); } /* cannot have both a NEW segment and ZERO points */
875 else{ return(1); } /* harmless - do nothing */
876 }
877 if(StartSeg && ((Elements - 1) % 3)){ return(0); } /* new segment must be 1 + N*3 points */
878 if(!StartSeg && (Elements % 3)){ return(0); } /* extend segment must be N*3 points */
879 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *tpo;
880 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *tpo2;
881 uint8_t First, Others;
882
883 tpo = U_PMF_POINTF_set(Elements, Points);
884 tpo2 = U_PO_po_append(Path->poPoints, tpo, U_PMF_DROP_ELEMENTS1);
885 U_PO_free(&tpo);
886 if(!tpo2)return(0);
887 Path->poPoints = tpo2;
888
889 if(StartSeg){ First = (Flags & U_PTP_NotClose0x70) | U_PPT_Start0x00; }
890 else { First = (Flags & U_PTP_NotClose0x70) | U_PPT_Bezier0x03; }
891 Others = (Flags & U_PTP_NotClose0x70) | U_PPT_Bezier0x03;
892 tpo = U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPE_set2(Elements, First, Others);
893 if(!tpo){ return(0); }
894 tpo2 = U_PO_po_append(Path->poTypes, tpo, U_PMF_DROP_ELEMENTS1);
895 U_PO_free(&tpo);
896 if(!tpo2)return(0);
897 Path->poTypes = tpo2;
898
899 Path->Elements += Elements;
900 return(1);
901}
902
903/**
904 \brief Append a "polygon" set of points to a path.
905 \param Path Address of a DoublePseudoObject holding the path to append to.
906 \param Elements number of Points and Flags
907 \param Points Line points.
908 \param Flags Flags (U_PTP_None, U_PTP_DashMode, U_PTP_PathMarker, U_PTP_NoBit, but NOT U_PTP_CloseSubpath)
909 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
910*/
911int U_PATH_polygon(U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *Path, uint32_t Elements, const U_PMF_POINTF *Points, uint8_t Flags){
912 int status = U_PATH_polylineto(Path, Elements, Points, Flags, U_SEG_NEW1);
913 if(status){
914 status = U_PATH_closepath(Path);
915 }
916 return(status);
917}
918
919//! \cond
920// These are not exposed in the API
921/* Parameterized Ellipse coordinates */
922U_PMF_POINTF U_eparam(U_FLOAT a, U_FLOAT b, U_PMF_POINTF *center, double Ang, double Theta){
923 U_PMF_POINTF point;
924 point.X = center->X + a*cos(Theta)*cos(Ang) - b*sin(Theta)*sin(Ang);
925 point.Y = center->Y + a*sin(Theta)*cos(Ang) + b*cos(Theta)*sin(Ang);
926 return(point);
927}
928
929/* Parameterized Ellipse derivative */
930U_PMF_POINTF U_eparam2(U_FLOAT a, U_FLOAT b, double Ang, double Theta){
931 U_PMF_POINTF point;
932 point.X = -a*cos(Theta)*sin(Ang) - b*sin(Theta)*cos(Ang);
933 point.Y = -a*sin(Theta)*sin(Ang) + b*cos(Theta)*cos(Ang);
934 return(point);
935}
936
937double U_aparam(double Ang1, double Ang2){
938 double Alpha;
939 double t2;
940 t2 = tan((Ang2 - Ang1)/2.0);
941 t2 *= t2;
942 Alpha = sin(Ang2 - Ang1) * (sqrt(4 + 3*t2) -1.0)/3.0;
943 return(Alpha);
944}
945
946/* Parameterized Bezier point Q1 or Q2 derivative */
947U_PMF_POINTF U_qparam(double Alpha, double a, double b, U_PMF_POINTF *Point, double Ang, double Theta, int mode){
948 U_PMF_POINTF Q, Prime;
949 Prime = U_eparam2(a,b,Ang,Theta);
950 if(mode==1){ /* Q1, anything else is Q2*/
951 Q.X = Point->X + Alpha * Prime.X;
952 Q.Y = Point->Y + Alpha * Prime.Y;
953 }
954 else {
955 Q.X = Point->X - Alpha * Prime.X;
956 Q.Y = Point->Y - Alpha * Prime.Y;
957 }
958 return(Q);
959}
960//! \endcond
961
962/**
963 \brief Append an "arcto" set of points to a path (Bezier points are calculated, and these are appended
964 \param Path Address of a pointer to the U_PSEUDO_OBJ that holds points
965 \param Start Start angle, >=0.0, degrees clockwise from 3:00
966 \param Sweep Sweep angle, -360<= angle <=360, degrees clockwise from Start
967 \param Rot Rotation angle to apply to coordinate system (Start and Rect), positive is degrees clockwise
968 \param Rect U_PMF_RECTF that defines the bounding rectangle.
969 \param Flags Flags (U_PTP_None, U_PTP_DashMode, U_PTP_PathMarker, U_PTP_NoBit, but NOT U_PTP_CloseSubpath)
970 \param StartSeg If set, the arc starts a new segment, if clear, continue the existing segment. Starting a new segment does not automatically apply U_PATH_closepath to the existing path.
971 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
972
973 Based on Luc Maisonobe's work, http://www.spaceroots.org/documents/ellipse/
974*/
975int U_PATH_arcto(U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *Path, U_FLOAT Start, U_FLOAT Sweep, U_FLOAT Rot, U_PMF_RECTF *Rect, uint8_t Flags, int StartSeg){
976 U_PMF_POINTF Bz[3];
977 U_PMF_POINTF Center;
978 U_PMF_POINTF P1,P2;
979 double a, b;
980 int done = 0;
981 int fpoint = 0;
982 double L1, L2; /* These are degrees CounterClockwise from 3:00 */
983 double Ang1, Ang2; /* These are parametric angles, derived from L1, L2*/
984 double Alpha; /* Dimensionless number used for Q1, Q2 */
985 double Theta; /* Rot in radians */
986 double Slop; /* do not let rounding errors cause spurious end points */
987 if(!Path){ return(0); }
988 if((Sweep > 360.0) || (Sweep < -360.0)){ return(0); }
989 /* Start should be between 0 and 360 degrees, but it does not really matter because sin, and cos will accept anything */
990 /* the sign on Sweep and Start is correct bacause LM's derivation has y positive up, but GDI+ has y positive down. */
991 a = Rect->Width/2.0;
992 b = Rect->Height/2.0;
993 if(!a || !b){ return(0); }
994 Center.X = Rect->X + a;
995 Center.Y = Rect->Y + b;
996 /* convert to radians */
997 Start = (2.0 * U_PI3.14159265358979323846 * Start)/360.0;
998 Sweep = (2.0 * U_PI3.14159265358979323846 * Sweep)/360.0;
999 Theta = (2.0 * U_PI3.14159265358979323846 * Rot )/360.0;
1000 Slop = Sweep/100000.0;
1001 L1 = Start;
1002
1003 while(!done){
1004 if(Sweep < 0){
1005 L2 = L1 - U_PI3.14159265358979323846/2.0;
1006 if(L2 <= Sweep + Start - Slop){ L2 = Sweep + Start; done = 1; }
1007 else {done = 0; }
1008 }
1009 else {
1010 L2 = L1 + U_PI3.14159265358979323846/2.0;
1011 if(L2 >= Sweep + Start + Slop){ L2 = Sweep + Start; done = 1; }
1012 else {done = 0; }
1013 }
1014 Ang1 = atan2(sin(L1)/b, cos(L1)/a);
1015 Ang2 = atan2(sin(L2)/b, cos(L2)/a);
1016 Alpha = U_aparam(Ang1, Ang2);
1017 P1 = U_eparam(a, b, &Center, Ang1, Theta); /* P1 */
1018 P2 = U_eparam(a, b, &Center, Ang2, Theta); /* P2 */
1019 Bz[0] = U_qparam(Alpha, a, b, &P1, Ang1, Theta, 1); /* Q1 */
1020 Bz[1] = U_qparam(Alpha, a, b, &P2, Ang2, Theta, 2); /* Q2 */
1021 Bz[2] = P2;
1022 if(!fpoint){
1023 if(StartSeg){ U_PATH_moveto(Path, P1, Flags); }
1024 else { U_PATH_lineto(Path, P1, Flags); }
1025 fpoint = 1;
1026 }
1027 U_PATH_polybezierto(Path, 3, Bz, Flags, U_SEG_OLD0 );
1028 L1 = L2;
1029 }
1030 return(1);
1031}
1032
1033/**
1034 \brief Allocate and construct an array of U_PMF_POINTF objects which have been subjected to a U_XFORM
1035 \returns pointer to an array of U_PMF_POINTF structures.
1036 \param points pointer to the source U_PMF_POINTF structures
1037 \param count number of members in points
1038 \param xform U_XFORM to apply
1039
1040*/
1041U_PMF_POINTF *pointfs_transform(U_PMF_POINTF *points, int count, U_XFORM xform){
1042 U_PMF_POINTF *newpts=NULL((void*)0);;
1043 int i;
1044 float X,Y;
1045 newpts = (U_PMF_POINTF *) malloc(count * sizeof(U_PMF_POINTF));
1046 if(newpts){
1047 for(i=0; i<count; i++){
1048 X = points[i].X;
1049 Y = points[i].Y;
1050 newpts[i].X = U_ROUND(X * xform.eM11 + Y * xform.eM21 + xform.eDx)( (X * xform.eM11 + Y * xform.eM21 + xform.eDx) > 0 ? floor
((X * xform.eM11 + Y * xform.eM21 + xform.eDx)+0.5) : ( (X * xform
.eM11 + Y * xform.eM21 + xform.eDx) < 0 ? -floor(-(X * xform
.eM11 + Y * xform.eM21 + xform.eDx)+0.5) : (X * xform.eM11 + Y
* xform.eM21 + xform.eDx) ) );
1051 newpts[i].Y = U_ROUND(X * xform.eM12 + Y * xform.eM22 + xform.eDy)( (X * xform.eM12 + Y * xform.eM22 + xform.eDy) > 0 ? floor
((X * xform.eM12 + Y * xform.eM22 + xform.eDy)+0.5) : ( (X * xform
.eM12 + Y * xform.eM22 + xform.eDy) < 0 ? -floor(-(X * xform
.eM12 + Y * xform.eM22 + xform.eDy)+0.5) : (X * xform.eM12 + Y
* xform.eM22 + xform.eDy) ) );
1052 }
1053 }
1054 return(newpts);
1055}
1056
1057/**
1058 \brief Allocate and construct an array of U_PMF_RECTF objects which have been subjected to a U_XFORM
1059 \returns pointer to an array of U_PMF_RECTF structures.
1060 \param Rects pointer to the source U_PMF_RECTF structures
1061 \param Count number of members in Rects
1062 \param Xform U_XFORM to apply. Rotation is ignored, only translation is applied.
1063
1064*/
1065U_PMF_RECTF *rectfs_transform(U_PMF_RECTF *Rects, int Count, U_XFORM Xform){
1066 U_PMF_RECTF *newRects;
1067 int i;
1068 newRects = (U_PMF_RECTF *) malloc(Count * sizeof(U_PMF_RECTF));
1069 if(newRects){
1070 for(i=0; i<Count; i++){
1071 newRects[i].X = U_ROUND(Rects[i].X + Xform.eDx)( (Rects[i].X + Xform.eDx) > 0 ? floor((Rects[i].X + Xform
.eDx)+0.5) : ( (Rects[i].X + Xform.eDx) < 0 ? -floor(-(Rects
[i].X + Xform.eDx)+0.5) : (Rects[i].X + Xform.eDx) ) );
1072 newRects[i].Y = U_ROUND(Rects[i].Y + Xform.eDy)( (Rects[i].Y + Xform.eDy) > 0 ? floor((Rects[i].Y + Xform
.eDy)+0.5) : ( (Rects[i].Y + Xform.eDy) < 0 ? -floor(-(Rects
[i].Y + Xform.eDy)+0.5) : (Rects[i].Y + Xform.eDy) ) );
1073 newRects[i].Width = U_ROUND(Rects[i].Width)( (Rects[i].Width) > 0 ? floor((Rects[i].Width)+0.5) : ( (
Rects[i].Width) < 0 ? -floor(-(Rects[i].Width)+0.5) : (Rects
[i].Width) ) );
1074 newRects[i].Height = U_ROUND(Rects[i].Height)( (Rects[i].Height) > 0 ? floor((Rects[i].Height)+0.5) : (
(Rects[i].Height) < 0 ? -floor(-(Rects[i].Height)+0.5) : (
Rects[i].Height) ) );
1075 }
1076 }
1077 return(newRects);
1078}

1080/**
1081 \brief Utility function calculate the transformation matrix needed to make a gradient run precisely corner to corner of a rectangle
1082 \param Angle Rotation in degrees clockwise of the gradient. 0 is horizontal gradient.
1083 \param w Width of the rectangle
1084 \param h Height of the rectangle
1085 \param x X coordinate of upper left corner of rectangle
1086 \param y Y coordinate of upper left corner of rectangle
1087 \param Periods Periods of gradient corner to corner. 1.0 is one, corner to corner.
1088 \return Transformation matrix. All values are zero if Periods, w, or h are less than or equal to zero.
1089*/
1090U_PMF_TRANSFORMMATRIX tm_for_gradrect(U_FLOAT Angle, U_FLOAT w, U_FLOAT h, U_FLOAT x, U_FLOAT y, U_FLOAT Periods){
1091//! \cond
1092#define CLOSE_TO_IS_REALLY_ZERO(A) ((A) > 1.0e-10 || (A) < -1.0e-10 ? (A) : 0.0) //! \hideinitializer
1093//! \endcond
1094 U_PMF_TRANSFORMMATRIX tm;
1095 double dang = Angle * 2*U_PI3.14159265358979323846 /360.0;
1096 double scale;
1097 double cd,sd;
1098 if((Periods <=0.0) || (w <= 0.0) || (h <= 0.0)){
1099 tm.m11 = tm.m12 = tm.m21 = tm.m22 = tm.dX = tm.dY = 0.0;
1100 }
1101 else {
1102 /*
1103 scale is gradient period divided by w
1104 The scale value sets the gradient period to match exactly with the inscribed (w,h) rectangle
1105 in the direction specified by the angle.
1106 The numberator of scale is the max of the four dot product values of the rotated X basis unit vector with (w,h),
1107 with each of the vectors {w,h}, {-w,h}, {-w,-h}, {w,h}. Those vectors run from each corner in turn
1108 to the opposite corner. The one most parallel to the rotated unit vector will have both terms positive.
1109
1110 Trig results like cos(pi/2) are not stable between platforms due to minor differences in the
1111 implementation. Detect these and make them zero, which then allows binary comparison of output files.
1112 Otherwise the binary comparisons between platforms would fail because of a bunch of insignificant digits.
1113 */
1114 cd = CLOSE_TO_IS_REALLY_ZERO(cos(dang));
1115 sd = CLOSE_TO_IS_REALLY_ZERO(sin(dang));
1116 scale = (w*fabs(cd) + h*fabs(sd))/(w*Periods);
1117 tm.m11 = scale * cd;
1118 tm.m12 = -scale * sd;
1119 tm.m21 = scale * sd;
1120 tm.m22 = scale * cd;
1121 /* offset is to one corner of the square, depending on which quadrant the rotation selects. */
1122 if(cos(dang)>=0){
1123 tm.dX = x;
1124 if(sin(dang)>=0){tm.dY = y + h; } // LL corner
1125 else { tm.dY = y; } // UL corner
1126 }
1127 else {
1128 tm.dX = x + w;
1129 if(sin(dang)>=0){ tm.dY = y + h; } // LR corner
1130 else { tm.dY = y; } // UR corner
1131 }
1132 }
1133 return tm;
1134#undef CLOSE_TO_IS_REALLY_ZERO
1135}
1136/**
1137 \brief Create a U_PSEUDO_OBJ containing a U_PMR_FILLPATH and U_PMR_DRAWPATH records.
1138 \returns pointer to U_PSEUDO_OBJ or NULL on error.
1139 \param PathID U_PMF_PATH object in the EMF+ object table (0-63, inclusive)
1140 \param PenID U_PMF_PEN object in the EMF+ object table (0-63, inclusive)
1141 \param BrushID U_PSEUDO_OBJ containing a U_PMF_ARGB or a U_PMF_4NUM. Color or U_PMF_BRUSH object in the EMF+ object table (0-63, inclusive)
1142*/
1143U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMR_drawfill(uint32_t PathID, uint32_t PenID, const U_PSEUDO_OBJ *BrushID){
1144 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMR_FILLPATH_set(PathID, BrushID);
1145 if(po){
1146 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *tpo = U_PMR_DRAWPATH_set(PathID, PenID);
1147 po = U_PO_po_append(po, tpo, U_PMF_KEEP_ELEMENTS0);
1148 U_PO_free(&tpo);
1149 }
1150 return(po);
1151}

1154
1155/**
1156 \brief Extract a single data field from a source.
1157 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
1158 \param Src where the data is coming from. It is incremented by the number of bytes retrieved.
1159 \param Dst where the data will be stored. This must either be NULL (in which case the Src
1160 is advanced and nothing is stored, or it must be allocated to Reps * Units bytes!!!!
1161 \param Units number of bytes in each unit of the data field
1162 \param Reps number of repeats of units in the data field.
1163 If a Ptr is NULL, then Units*Reps 0 bytes are stored.
1164 If a Ptr is NOT NULL, and Units or Reps, is zero an error is signaled.
1165 If a Ptr is NULL and Units*Reps is 0, nothing happens.
1166 \param SE logical (Source Endian). Only relevant for Sizes of 2 or 4
1167 Indicates when Bytes may need to be rearranged when they are retrieved.
1168 U_XE no change (this is used when the data has already been set to the proper orientation or it is not known)
1169 U_LE source is Little Endian
1170 U_BE source is Big Endian.
1171 U_XX error
1172
1173*/
1174int U_PMF_SERIAL_get(const char **Src, void *Dst, size_t Units, size_t Reps, int SE){
1175 if(!Src || !*Src || SE == U_XX0xFF){ return(0); }
1176 U_PMF_MEMCPY_SRCSHIFT(Dst, Src, Units * Reps);
1177 if(!Dst){ return(1); } /* "fake" get, no data was retrieved, so we are done */
1178 if(SE == U_XE0){ return(1); }
1179 if(SE == U_LE1 && U_IS_LE1){ return(1); }
1180 if(SE == U_BE2 && U_IS_BE0){ return(1); }
1181 /* need to swap */
1182 if( Units==2){ U_swap2(Dst,Reps); }
1183 else if(Units==4){ U_swap4(Dst,Reps); }
1184 return(1);
1185}
1186
1187/**
1188 \brief Conditionally extract an array of data from a source, allocating space to hold it.
1189 \returns 1 on success, 0 on error.
1190 \param Src where the data is coming from. It is incremented by the number of bytes retrieved.
1191 \param Dst Caller must free. Where the pointer to the data will be stored. Reps * Units bytes will be allocated,
1192 \param Units number of bytes in each unit of the data field
1193 \param Reps number of repeats of units in the data field.
1194 If a Ptr is NULL, then Units*Reps 0 bytes are stored.
1195 If a Ptr is NOT NULL, and Units or Reps, is zero an error is signaled.
1196 If a Ptr is NULL and Units*Reps is 0, nothing happens.
1197 \param SE logical (Source Endian). Only relevant for Sizes of 2 or 4
1198 Indicates when Bytes may need to be rearranged when they are retrieved.
1199 U_XE no change (this is used when the data has already been set to the proper orientation or it is not known)
1200 U_LE source is Little Endian
1201 U_BE source is Big Endian.
1202 U_XX error
1203 \param Cond Store the data into *Dst if true, set *Dst to NULL otherwise.
1204
1205*/
1206int U_PMF_SERIAL_array_copy_get(const char **Src, void **Dst, size_t Units, size_t Reps, int SE, int Cond){
1207 if(!Src || !*Src || !Dst || SE == U_XX0xFF){ return(0); }
1208 if(!Cond){
1209 *Src += Units * Reps;
1210 *Dst = NULL((void*)0);
1211 return(1);
1212 }
1213 *Dst = malloc(Units * Reps);
1214 if(!*Dst){ return(1); } /* "fake" get, no data was retrieved, so we are done */
1215 U_PMF_MEMCPY_SRCSHIFT(*Dst, Src, Units * Reps);
1216 if(SE == U_XE0){ return(1); }
1217 if(SE == U_LE1 && U_IS_LE1){ return(1); }
1218 if(SE == U_BE2 && U_IS_BE0){ return(1); }
1219 /* need to swap */
1220 if( Units==2){ U_swap2(*Dst,Reps); }
1221 else if(Units==4){ U_swap4(*Dst,Reps); }
1222 return(1);
1223}

1227/**
1228 \brief Calculate the length in bytes of a relative path object composed of U_PMF_INTEGER7 and U_PMF_INTER15 values
1229 \return >=0 length == success, <0 error
1230 \param contents Start of a relative path consisting of int7 and int15 X,Y pairs.
1231 \param Elements number of relative X,Y pairs in the object
1232*/
1233int U_PMF_LEN_REL715(const char *contents, int Elements){
1234 int length=0;
1235 Elements *= 2; /* N pairs = 2N values */
1236 for( ; Elements; Elements--){
1237 /* X or Y value */
1238 if(*contents & U_TEST_INT70x80){ contents +=2; length +=2; } //int15
1239 else { contents +=1; length +=1; } //int7
1240 }
1241 return(length);
1242}

1244/**
1245 \brief Calculate the length in bytes of objects which are a 4 byte Count followed by Count * float bytes
1246 \return >=0 length == success, <0 error
1247 Object types whose size may be derived with this function are:
1248 U_PMF_COMPOUNDLINEDATA
1249 U_PMF_DASHEDLINEDATA
1250*/
1251int U_PMF_LEN_FLOATDATA(const char *contents){
1252 int Size;
1253 U_PMF_SERIAL_get(&contents, &Size, 4, 1, U_LE1);
1254 Size = 4*Size + 4;
1255 return(Size);
1256}

1258/**
1259 \brief Calculate the length in bytes of objects which are a 4 byte count followed by count bytes
1260 \return >=0 length == success, <0 error
1261 Object types whose size may be derived with this function are:
1262 U_PMF_BOUNDARYPATHDATA
1263 U_PMF_BOUNDARYPOINTDATA
1264 U_PMF_CUSTOMSTARTCAPDATA
1265 U_PMF_PATH
1266 U_PMF_LINEPATH
1267 U_PMF_REGIONNODEPATH
1268*/
1269int U_PMF_LEN_BYTEDATA(const char *contents){
1270 int Size;
1271 U_PMF_SERIAL_get(&contents, &Size, 4, 1, U_LE1);
1272 Size += 4;
1273 return(Size);
1274}

1276/**

1278 \return number of bytes in record, 0 on error
1279 \param GUID pointer to the 16 unsigned bytes
1280 \return string in curly bracket form.
1281 http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/cc230316.aspx
1282
1283 Text form is Data1-Data2-Data3-Data4, the first 3 are stored as little endian integers, the last as a string (big endian).
1284*/
1285char *U_PMF_CURLYGUID_set(uint8_t *GUID){

1287 if(string){
1288 sprintf(string,"{%2.2X%2.2X%2.2X%2.2X-%2.2X%2.2X-%2.2X%2.2X-%2.2X%2.2X-%2.2X%2.2X%2.2X%2.2X%2.2X%2.2X}",
1289 GUID[3],GUID[2],GUID[1],GUID[0],
1290 GUID[5],GUID[4],
1291 GUID[7],GUID[6],
1292 GUID[8],GUID[9],
1293 GUID[10],GUID[11],GUID[12],GUID[13],GUID[14],GUID[15]
1294 );
1295 }
1296 return(string);
1297}

1305*/
1306int U_PMF_KNOWNCURLYGUID_set(const char *string){

1322
1323/** \brief Load a GUID from text format into EMF+ file binary format.
1324 \param string Curly GUID as text, minus the barckets and dashes.
1325 \return GUID in EMF+ file binary format.
1326
1327
1328This accepts a string that is 16 bytes long = 32 characters hex (no dash spaces or brackets) as text.
1329Text form is; Data1|Data2|Data3|Data4, first three are stored as little endian integers of 4,2,2 bytes, respectively,
1330last is stored like a string (big endian), after conversion from text hex to binary.
1331
1332This function is not normally called by end user code.
1333*/
1334uint8_t *U_LOAD_GUID(char *string){
1335 uint32_t Data1,tData2,tData3,tByte;
1336 uint16_t Data2,Data3;
1337 char *Data4 = string + 16;
1338 uint8_t *hold = malloc(16);
1339 char *lf = (char *) hold;
1340 int i;
1341 if(hold){
1342 Data1=tData2=tData3=0;
1343 if(3 != sscanf(string + 0,"%8X",&Data1) +
1344 sscanf(string + 8,"%4X",&tData2) +
1345 sscanf(string + 12,"%4X",&tData3)){
1346 free(hold);
1347 hold = NULL((void*)0);
1348 goto bye;
1349 }
1350 Data2=tData2;
1351 Data3=tData3;
1352 U_PMF_MEMCPY_DSTSHIFT(&lf, &Data1, 4);
1353 U_PMF_MEMCPY_DSTSHIFT(&lf, &Data2, 2);
1354 U_PMF_MEMCPY_DSTSHIFT(&lf, &Data3, 2);
1355 if(U_IS_BE0){ /* these fields are stored little endian */
1356 U_swap4(hold,1);
1357 U_swap2(hold+4,2);
1358 }
1359 /* remainder is converted byte by byte and stored in that order */
1360 for(i=0;i<8;i++,Data4+=2,lf++){
1361 if(1 != sscanf(Data4,"%2X",&tByte)){
1362 free(hold);
1363 hold = NULL((void*)0);
1364 goto bye;
1365 }
1366 *lf=tByte;
1367 }
1368 }
1369bye:
1370 return(hold);
1371}
1372
1373/**
1374 \brief Generate the 16 byte form from OID of the ImageEffects Identifier
1375 \param OID OID of the ImageEffects Identifier
1376 \return pointer to 16 byte buffer holding the long GUID binary form, or NULL on error.
1377
1378 EMF+ manual 2.1.3.1, Microsoft name: ImageEffects Identifier
1379*/
1380uint8_t *U_OID_To_GUID(uint32_t OID){
1381 uint8_t *lf = NULL((void*)0);
1382 if( OID == U_PMF_IE_BLUR_OID0x02020301 ){ lf = U_LOAD_GUID("633C80A41843482B9EF2BE2834C5FDD4"); }
1383 else if(OID == U_PMF_IE_BRIGHTNESSCONTRAST_OID0x02020302 ){ lf = U_LOAD_GUID("D3A1DBE18EC44C179F4CEA97AD1C343D"); }
1384 else if(OID == U_PMF_IE_COLORBALANCE_OID0x02020303 ){ lf = U_LOAD_GUID("537E597D251E48DA966429CA496B70F8"); }
1385 else if(OID == U_PMF_IE_COLORCURVE_OID0x02020304 ){ lf = U_LOAD_GUID("DD6A002258E44A679D9BD48EB881A53D"); }
1386 else if(OID == U_PMF_IE_COLORLOOKUPTABLE_OID0x02020305 ){ lf = U_LOAD_GUID("A7CE72A90F7F40D7B3CCD0C02D5C3212"); }
1387 else if(OID == U_PMF_IE_COLORMATRIX_OID0x02020306 ){ lf = U_LOAD_GUID("718F2615793340E3A5115F68FE14DD74"); }
1388 else if(OID == U_PMF_IE_HUESATURATIONLIGHTNESS_OID0x02020307){ lf = U_LOAD_GUID("8B2DD6C3EB074D87A5F07108E26A9C5F"); }
1389 else if(OID == U_PMF_IE_LEVELS_OID0x02020308 ){ lf = U_LOAD_GUID("99C354EC2A314F3A8C3417A803B33A25"); }
1390 else if(OID == U_PMF_IE_REDEYECORRECTION_OID0x02020309 ){ lf = U_LOAD_GUID("74D29D0569A4426695493CC52836B632"); }
1391 else if(OID == U_PMF_IE_SHARPEN_OID0x02020310 ){ lf = U_LOAD_GUID("63CBF3EEC526402C8F7162C540BF5142"); }
1392 else if(OID == U_PMF_IE_TINT_OID0x02020311 ){ lf = U_LOAD_GUID("1077AF0028484441948944AD4C2D7A2C"); }
1393 return(lf);
1394}

1396/**
1397 \brief copy data and shift source pointer by the amount of data moved
1398 \param Dst Destination in memory
1399 \param Src Source in memory
1400 \param Size Number of bytes to move
1401*/
1402void U_PMF_MEMCPY_SRCSHIFT(void *Dst, const char **Src, size_t Size){
1403 if(Dst)memcpy(Dst, *Src, Size);
1404 *Src += Size;
1405}
1406
1407/**
1408 \brief copy data and shift destination pointer by the amount of data moved
1409 \param Dst Destination in memory (this must not be NULL)
1410 \param Src Source in memory (if this is NULL, fill with that many zero bytes instead)
1411 \param Size Number of bytes to move
1412*/
1413void U_PMF_MEMCPY_DSTSHIFT(char **Dst, const void *Src, size_t Size){
1414 if(Src){ memcpy(*Dst, Src, Size); }
1415 else { memset(*Dst, 0, Size); }
1416 *Dst += Size;
1417}
1418
1419/**
1420 \brief Copy the single instance at Src repeatedly to Dst.
1421 \param Dst Destination in memory
1422 \param Src Source in memory (if this is NULL, fill with that many zero bytes instead)
1423 \param Size number of bytes in single instance that is template.
1424 \param Reps Number of instances of the template to opy
1425*/
1426void U_PMF_REPCPY_DSTSHIFT(char **Dst, const void *Src, size_t Size, size_t Reps){
1427 for(;Reps;Reps--){
1428 if(Src){ memcpy(*Dst, Src, Size); }
1429 else { memset(*Dst, 0, Size); }
1430 *Dst += Size;
1431 }
1432}
1433
1434/**
1435 \brief save pointer to data and shift source pointer by the amount of data moved
1436 \param Dst Destination in memory
1437 \param Src Source in memory or NULL. If NULL Dst is set to NULL.
1438 \param Size Number of bytes to move
1439*/
1440void U_PMF_PTRSAV_SHIFT(const char **Dst, const char **Src, size_t Size){
1441 if(*Src){
1442 if(Dst)*Dst = *Src;
1443 *Src += Size;
1444 }
1445 else {
1446 if(Dst)*Dst = NULL((void*)0);
1447 }
1448}
1449
1450/**
1451 \brief save pointer to data and shift source pointer by the amount of data moved
1452 \return 1 on sucess, 0 on error
1453 \param Dst Destination in memory
1454 \param Src Source in memory or NULL. If NULL Dst is set to NULL.
1455 \param Doit Assign if true, otherwise, set to NULL
1456*/
1457int U_PMF_PTRSAV_COND(const char **Dst, const char *Src, int Doit){
1458 if(!Dst){ return(0); }
1459 if(Src && Doit){ *Dst = Src; }
1460 else { *Dst = NULL((void*)0); }
1461 return(1);
1462}

1464
1465 =====================================================================================
1466 start of U_PMF_*_get() functions
1467
1468*/
1469
1470/**
1471 \brief Get the 16 bit unsigned Flags field from a header.
1472 \param contents Record from which to extract data, will be incremented by header size.
1473 \return Flags field
1474
1475 In many records the only value needed from the header is Flags. Rather than mapping
1476 the entire Header and returning it, in these instances this function may be called to
1477 just get this one value.
1478*/
1479uint16_t U_PMF_HEADERFLAGS_get(const char *contents){
1480 uint16_t Flags;
1481 const char *cptr = contents + offsetof(U_PMF_CMN_HDR,Flags)__builtin_offsetof(U_PMF_CMN_HDR, Flags);
1482 U_PMF_SERIAL_get(&cptr, &Flags, 2, 1, U_LE1); /* EMF+ manual documents it as BE, but this code implements it as LE*/
1483 return(Flags);
1484}
1485
1486/**
1487 \brief Retrieve whichever header fields are requested. NULL pointers do not retrieve.
1488 \param contents Record from which to extract data, will be incremented by header size.
1489 \param Type Record type
1490 \param Flags Record flags
1491 \param Size Records size
1492 \param Datasize Data size
1493 \return 1 on success, 0 on failure.
1494*/
1495int U_PMF_HEADERFIELDS_get(const char *contents,
1496 uint16_t *Type, uint16_t *Flags, uint32_t *Size, uint32_t *Datasize){
1497 if(!contents){ return(0); }
1498 U_PMF_SERIAL_get(&contents, Type, 2, 1, U_LE1);
1499 U_PMF_SERIAL_get(&contents, Flags, 2, 1, U_LE1); /* EMF+ manual documents it as BE, but this code implements it as LE*/
1500 U_PMF_SERIAL_get(&contents, Size, 4, 1, U_LE1);
1501 U_PMF_SERIAL_get(&contents, Datasize, 4, 1, U_LE1);
1502 return(1);
1503}
1504

1512int U_PMF_CMN_HDR_get(const char **contents, U_PMF_CMN_HDR *Header){

1526/**
1527 \brief return the size in bytes of the EMF+ record
1528 \param contents Record from which to extract data, will not be modified.
1529 \returns size, or 0 if contents is Null
1530*/
1531int U_PMF_RECORD_SIZE_get(const char *contents){
1532 if(!contents){ return(0); }
1533 int Size;
1534 const char *from = contents + 4;
1535 U_PMF_SERIAL_get(&from, &Size, 4, 1, U_LE1);
1536 return(Size);
1537}
1538
1539/**
1540 \brief Return the size of a PenData object from an EMF+ record.
1541 \param PenData Address in memory where the PenData object starts.
1542 \returns size of the object in bytes
1543*/
1544int U_PMF_LEN_PENDATA(const char *PenData){
1545 uint32_t Flags;
1546 int length=12; /* Flags, Unit, Width */
1547 U_PMF_SERIAL_get(&PenData, &Flags, 4, 1, U_LE1);
1548 PenData += 8; /* skip Unit and Width */
1549 length += U_PMF_LEN_OPTPENDATA(PenData, Flags);
1550 return(length);
1551}
1552
1553/**
1554 \brief Return the size of an OptPenData object from an EMF+ record.
1555 \param PenData Address in memory where the PenData object starts.
1556 \param Flags PenData Flags that indicate which fields are present.
1557 \returns size of the object in bytes
1558*/
1559int U_PMF_LEN_OPTPENDATA(const char *PenData, uint32_t Flags){
1560 int length=0;
1561 if(Flags & U_PD_Transform0x0001){ length += sizeof(U_PMF_TRANSFORMMATRIX); }
1562 if(Flags & U_PD_StartCap0x0002){ length += sizeof(int32_t); }
1563 if(Flags & U_PD_EndCap0x0004){ length += sizeof(int32_t); }
1564 if(Flags & U_PD_Join0x0008){ length += sizeof(uint32_t); }
1565 if(Flags & U_PD_MiterLimit0x0010){ length += sizeof(U_FLOAT); }
1566 if(Flags & U_PD_LineStyle0x0020){ length += sizeof(int32_t); }
1567 if(Flags & U_PD_DLCap0x0040){ length += sizeof(int32_t); }
1568 if(Flags & U_PD_DLOffset0x0080){ length += sizeof(int32_t); }
1569 if(Flags & U_PD_DLData0x0100){ length += U_PMF_LEN_FLOATDATA(PenData + length); }
1570 if(Flags & U_PD_NonCenter0x0200){ length += sizeof(int32_t); }
1571 if(Flags & U_PD_CLData0x0400){ length += U_PMF_LEN_FLOATDATA(PenData + length); }
1572 if(Flags & U_PD_CustomStartCap0x0800){ length += U_PMF_LEN_BYTEDATA(PenData + length); }
1573 if(Flags & U_PD_CustomEndCap0x1000){ length += U_PMF_LEN_BYTEDATA(PenData + length); }
1574 return(length);
1575}

1699/**
1700 \brief Create and set a U_PMF_PATH PseudoObject
1701 \return Pointer to PseudoObject, NULL on error
1702 \param Version EmfPlusGraphicsVersion object
1703 \param Points U_PSEUDO_OBJ containing array of points (of type PMFPointR, PMFPoint, or PMFPointF, determined by U_PPF_P and U_PPF_C bits in Flags)
1704 \param Types U_PSEUDO_OBJ containing array of types (U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPE or U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPERLE, determined by U_PPF_R big in Flags)
1705
1706 EMF+ manual 2.2.1.6, Microsoft name: EmfPlusPath Object
1707*/
1708U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_PATH_set(uint32_t Version, const U_PSEUDO_OBJ *Points, const U_PSEUDO_OBJ *Types){
1709 int ctype, RelAbs, rtype;
1710 int pad;
1711 if(Points){
1712 if( Points->Type == U_PMF_POINTR_OID0x02020237){ RelAbs = 1; ctype = 0; }
1713 else if(Points->Type == (U_PMF_POINT_OID0x02020235 | U_PMF_ARRAY_OID0x80000000)){ RelAbs = 0; ctype = 1; }
1714 else if(Points->Type == (U_PMF_POINTF_OID0x02020236 | U_PMF_ARRAY_OID0x80000000)){ RelAbs = 0; ctype = 0; }
1715 else { return(NULL((void*)0)); }
1716 }
1717 else { return(NULL((void*)0)); }
1718 if(Types){
1719 if( Types->Type == (U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPERLE_OID0x02020232 | U_PMF_ARRAY_OID0x80000000)){ rtype = 1; }
1720 else if(Types->Type == (U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPE_OID0x02020231 | U_PMF_ARRAY_OID0x80000000)){ rtype = 0; }
1721 else { return(NULL((void*)0)); }
1722 }
1723 else { return(NULL((void*)0)); }
1724 uint16_t Flags = (rtype ? U_PPF_R0x1000 : 0) | (ctype ? U_PPF_C0x4000 : 0)| (RelAbs ? U_PPF_P0x0800 : 0);
1725 pad = (0x3 & (Points->Used + Types->Used));
1726 if(pad){ pad = 4 - pad; }
1727 const U_SERIAL_DESC List[] = {
1728 {&Version, 4, 1, U_LE1 },
1729 {Points->Data, 4, 1, U_XE0 }, /* Elements from Points */
1730 {&Flags, 2, 1, U_LE1 },
1731 {NULL((void*)0), 2, 1, U_LE1 }, /* Reserved field */
1732 {Points->Data + 4, Points->Used - 4, 1, U_XE0 }, /* omit Points Elements */
1733 {Types->Data +4, Types->Used - 4, 1, U_XE0 }, /* omit Types Elements */
1734 {NULL((void*)0), pad, (pad ? 1 : 0), (pad ? U_XE0 : U_XX0xFF)}, /* if no padding is needed the Units will be zero and nothing will happen */
1735 {NULL((void*)0),0,0,U_XX0xFF}
1736 };
1737 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMF_SERIAL_set(U_PMF_PATH_OID0x02020106, List);
1738 return(po);
1739}

1742/**
1743 \brief Create and set a U_PMF_PATH PseudoObject that uses U_PMF_POINTF coordinates
1744 \return Pointer to PseudoObject, NULL on error
1745 \param Version EmfPlusGraphicsVersion object
1746 \param Path U_DPSEUDO_OBJ containing a path.
1747
1748 EMF+ manual 2.2.1.6, Microsoft name: EmfPlusPath Object
1749*/
1750U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_PATH_set2(uint32_t Version, const U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *Path){
1751 if(!Path || !Path->Elements){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
1752 uint16_t Flags = 0;
1753 int pad = (0x3 & Path->Elements);
1754 if(pad){ pad = 4 - pad; }
1755 const U_SERIAL_DESC List[] = {
1756 {&Version, 4, 1, U_LE1 },
1757 {&Path->Elements, 4, 1, U_LE1 },
1758 {&Flags, 2, 1, U_LE1 },
1759 {NULL((void*)0), 2, 1, U_LE1 }, /* Reserved field */
1760 {Path->poPoints->Data, 4, 2*Path->Elements,U_XE0 }, /* raw OID, so no leading Elements to omit */
1761 {Path->poTypes->Data, 1, Path->Elements, U_XE0 }, /* raw OID, so no leading Elements to omit */
1762 {NULL((void*)0), pad, (pad ? 1 : 0), (pad ? U_XE0 : U_XX0xFF)}, /* if no padding is needed the Units will be zero and nothing will happen */
1763 {NULL((void*)0),0,0,U_XX0xFF}
1764 };
1765 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMF_SERIAL_set(U_PMF_PATH_OID0x02020106, List);
1766 return(po);
1767}

1769/**
1770 \brief Create and set a U_PMF_PATH PseudoObject that uses U_PMF_POINT (int 16) coordinates
1771 \return Pointer to PseudoObject, NULL on error
1772 \param Version EmfPlusGraphicsVersion object
1773 \param Path U_DPSEUDO_OBJ containing a path.
1774
1775 EMF+ manual 2.2.1.6, Microsoft name: EmfPlusPath Object
1776*/
1777U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_PATH_set3(uint32_t Version, const U_DPSEUDO_OBJ *Path){
1778 if(!Path || !Path->Elements){return(NULL((void*)0)); }
1779 uint16_t Flags = U_PPF_C0x4000;
1780 int pad = (0x3 & Path->Elements);
1781 if(pad){ pad = 4 - pad; }
1782 U_PMF_POINT *Points16 = POINTF_To_POINT16_LE((U_PMF_POINTF *)Path->poPoints->Data, Path->Elements);
1783 if(!Points16){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
1784 const U_SERIAL_DESC List[] = {
1785 {&Version, 4, 1, U_LE1 },
1786 {&Path->Elements, 4, 1, U_LE1 },
1787 {&Flags, 2, 1, U_LE1 },
1788 {NULL((void*)0), 2, 1, U_LE1 }, /* Reserved field */
1789 {Points16, 2, 2*Path->Elements,U_XE0 }, /* raw data, so no leading Elements to omit */
1790 {Path->poTypes->Data, 1, Path->Elements, U_XE0 }, /* raw data, so no leading Elements to omit */
1791 {NULL((void*)0), pad, (pad ? 1 : 0), (pad ? U_XE0 : U_XX0xFF)}, /* if no padding is needed the Units will be zero and nothing will happen */
1792 {NULL((void*)0),0,0,U_XX0xFF}
1793 };
1794 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMF_SERIAL_set(U_PMF_PATH_OID0x02020106, List);
1795 free(Points16);
1796 return(po);
1797}

2003/**
2004 \brief Create and set a U_PMF_BLENDCOLORS PseudoObject
2005 \return Pointer to PseudoObject, NULL on Positions and Colors
2006 \param Elements number of elements in Positions, must agree with the number of Colors.
2007 \param Positions positions along gradient line. The first position MUST be 0.0 and the last MUST be 1.0.
2008 \param Colors U_PSEUDO_OBJ containing an array of U_PMF_ARGB objects: object colors at positions on gradient line
2009
2010 EMF+ manual 2.2.2.4, Microsoft name: EmfPlusBlendColors Object
2011*/
2012U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_BLENDCOLORS_set(uint32_t Elements, const U_FLOAT *Positions, const U_PSEUDO_OBJ *Colors){
2013 if(!Colors || !Positions || Colors->Type != (U_PMF_ARGB_OID0x02020201 | U_PMF_ARRAY_OID0x80000000)){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
2014 uint32_t CElements = (Colors->Used - 4)/4;
2015 if(CElements != Elements){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
2016 const U_SERIAL_DESC List[] = {
2017 {&CElements, 4, 1, U_LE1},
2018 {Positions, 4, CElements, U_LE1},
2019 {Colors->Data + 4, Colors->Used - 4, 1, U_XE0}, /* omit Elements part of this PseudoObject */
2020 {NULL((void*)0),0,0,U_XX0xFF}
2021 };
2022 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMF_SERIAL_set(U_PMF_BLENDCOLORS_OID0x02020204, List);
2023 return(po);
2024}
2025
2026/**
2027 \brief Create and set a U_PMF_BLENDCOLORS PseudoObject
2028 \return Pointer to PseudoObject, NULL on error
2029 \param Elements members in osition, inluding Start and End (0.0 - 1.0)
2030 \param StartColor Start Color (U_PMF_ARGB)
2031 \param EndColor End Color (U_PMF_ARGB)
2032
2033 EMF+ manual 2.2.2.5, Microsoft name: EmfPlusBlendFactors Object
2034
2035
2036 Positions always start at 0.0 and always end at 1.0. It is not well documented but other
2037 start and end values generally do not work.
2038*/
2039U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_BLENDCOLORS_linear_set(uint32_t Elements, U_PMF_ARGB StartColor, U_PMF_ARGB EndColor){
2040 double dP,dR,dG,dB,dA,P,R,G,B,A;
2041 U_FLOAT StartPos = 0.0;
2042 U_FLOAT EndPos = 1.0;
2043 U_FLOAT *Positions;
2044 U_FLOAT *pP;
2045 U_PMF_ARGB *Colors;
2046 U_PMF_ARGB *pC;
2047 unsigned int i;
2048 if(Elements <= 2 ){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
2049 pP = Positions = (U_FLOAT *)malloc(Elements *sizeof(U_FLOAT));
2050 if(!Positions){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
2051 pC = Colors = (U_PMF_ARGB *)malloc(Elements *sizeof(U_PMF_ARGB));
2052 if(!Colors){
2053 free(Positions);
2054 return(NULL((void*)0));
2055 }
2056 dP = (EndPos - StartPos )/(float)(Elements - 1);
2057 dB = ((double)EndColor.Blue - (double)StartColor.Blue )/(double)(Elements - 1);
2058 dG = ((double)EndColor.Green - (double)StartColor.Green)/(double)(Elements - 1);
2059 dR = ((double)EndColor.Red - (double)StartColor.Red )/(double)(Elements - 1);
2060 dA = ((double)EndColor.Alpha - (double)StartColor.Alpha)/(double)(Elements - 1);
2061 P = StartPos;
2062 B = StartColor.Blue;
2063 G = StartColor.Green;
2064 R = StartColor.Red;
2065 A = StartColor.Alpha;
2066 for(i=0;i<Elements;i++,pC++,pP++){ /* hopefully the rounding errors are not a problem, used doubles to minimize that */
2067 *pP = P;
2068 P += dP;
2069 *pC = (U_PMF_ARGB){B,G,R,A};
2070 B += dB;
2071 G += dG;
2072 R += dR;
2073 A += dA;
2074 }
2075 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *poColors = U_PMF_ARGBN_set(Elements, Colors);
2076 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMF_BLENDCOLORS_set(Elements, Positions, poColors);
2077 U_PO_free(&poColors);
2078 free(Positions);
2079 free(Colors);
2080 return(po);
2081}
2082

2084/**
2085 \brief Create and set a U_PMF_BLENDFACTORS PseudoObject
2086 \return Pointer to PseudoObject, NULL on error
2087 \param Elements members in each array
2088 \param Positions positions along gradient line. The first position MUST be 0.0 and the last MUST be 1.0.
2089 \param Factors blending factors, 0.0->1.0 values, inclusive
2090
2091 EMF+ manual 2.2.2.5, Microsoft name: EmfPlusBlendFactors Object
2092*/
2093U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_BLENDFACTORS_set(uint32_t Elements, const U_FLOAT *Positions, const U_FLOAT *Factors){
2094 if(!Positions || !Factors)return(NULL((void*)0));
2095 const U_SERIAL_DESC List[] = {
2096 {&Elements, 4, 1, U_LE1},
2097 {Positions, 4, Elements, U_LE1},
2098 {Factors, 4, Elements, U_LE1},
2099 {NULL((void*)0),0,0,U_XX0xFF}
2100 };
2101 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMF_SERIAL_set(U_PMF_BLENDFACTORS_OID0x02020205, List);
2102 return(po);
2103}
2104
2105/**
2106 \brief Create and set a U_PMF_BLENDFACTORS PseudoObject
2107 \return Pointer to PseudoObject, NULL on error
2108 \param Elements members in osition, inluding Start and End (0.0 - 1.0)
2109 \param StartFactor Start Factor (0.0 - 1.0)
2110 \param EndFactor End Factor (0.0 - 1.0)
2111
2112 EMF+ manual 2.2.2.5, Microsoft name: EmfPlusBlendFactors Object
2113
2114
2115 Positions always start at 0.0 and always end at 1.0. It is not well documented but other
2116 start and end values generally do not work.
2117*/
2118U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_BLENDFACTORS_linear_set(uint32_t Elements, U_FLOAT StartFactor, U_FLOAT EndFactor){
2119 double dP,dF,P,F;
2120 U_FLOAT StartPos = 0.0;
2121 U_FLOAT EndPos = 1.0;
2122 U_FLOAT *Positions;
2123 U_FLOAT *Factors;
2124 U_FLOAT *pP;
2125 U_FLOAT *pF;
2126 unsigned int i;
2127 if(Elements <= 2 ){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
2128 pP = Positions = (U_FLOAT *)malloc(Elements *sizeof(U_FLOAT));
2129 if(!Positions){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
2130 pF = Factors = (U_FLOAT *)malloc(Elements *sizeof(U_FLOAT));
2131 if(!Factors){
2132 free(Positions);
2133 return(NULL((void*)0));
2134 }
2135 dP = (EndPos - StartPos )/(float)(Elements - 1);
2136 dF = (EndFactor - StartFactor)/(float)(Elements - 1);
2137 P = StartPos;
2138 F = StartFactor;
2139 for(i=0;i<Elements;i++){ /* hopefully the rounding errors are not a problem, used doubles to minimize that */
2140 *pP++ = P; P += dP;
2141 *pF++ = F; F += dF;
2142 }
2143 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMF_BLENDFACTORS_set(Elements, Positions, Factors);
2144 free(Positions);
2145 free(Factors);
2146 return(po);
2147}

2249 EMF+ manual 2.2.2.11, Microsoft name: EmfPlusCustomEndCapData Object
2250*/
2251U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_CUSTOMENDCAPDATA_set(const U_PSEUDO_OBJ *Clc){
2252 if(!Clc || Clc->Type != U_PMF_CUSTOMLINECAP_OID0x02020102)return(NULL((void*)0));

2254 uint32_t Used = Clc->Used;
2255 const U_SERIAL_DESC List[] = {
2256 {&Used, 4, 1, U_LE1},
2257 {Clc->Data, Clc->Used, 1, U_XE0},

2395/**
2396 \brief Utility function to create and set a U_PMF_DASHEDLINEDATA PseudoObject from one of a predefined set of patterns
2397 \return Pointer to PseudoObject, NULL on error
2398 \param Unit Length of the repeat unit
2399 \param StdPat Members in Lengths
2400
2401 EMF+ manual 2.2.2.16, Microsoft name: EmfPlusDashedLineData Object
2402*/
2403U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_DASHEDLINEDATA_set2(U_FLOAT Unit, int StdPat){
2404 uint32_t Elements;
2405 uint8_t *p;
2406 U_FLOAT SubUnit;
2407 U_FLOAT Lengths[8]; /* This is the most dash/spaces that will be needed*/
2408 int i;
2409 /* Dot = 1, Dash = 2; Long = 3, 0 = terminate pattern */
2410 uint8_t SB[U_DD_Types27][5] =
2411 {
2412 {0,0,0,0,0}, // Solid
2413 {2,0,0,0,0}, // Dash
2414 {2,2,0,0,0}, // DashDash
2415 {2,2,2,0,0}, // DashDashDash
2416 {2,2,2,2,0}, // DashDashDashDash
2417 {1,0,0,0,0}, // Dot
2418 {1,1,0,0,0}, // DotDot
2419 {1,1,1,0,0}, // DotDotDot
2420 {1,1,1,1,0}, // DotDotDotDot
2421 {2,1,0,0,0}, // DashDot
2422 {2,2,1,0,0}, // DashDashDot
2423 {2,2,1,1,0}, // DashDashDotDot
2424 {2,2,2,1,0}, // DashDashDashDot
2425 {2,1,1,0,0}, // DashDotDot
2426 {2,1,1,1,0}, // DashDotDotDot
2427 {2,1,2,1,0}, // DashDotDashDot
2428 {3,0,0,0,0}, // Long
2429 {3,3,0,0,0}, // LongLong
2430 {3,3,3,0,0}, // LongLongLong
2431 {3,3,3,3,0}, // LongLongLongLong
2432 {3,1,0,0,0}, // LongDot
2433 {3,3,1,0,0}, // LongLongDot
2434 {3,3,1,1,0}, // LongLongDotDot
2435 {3,3,3,1,0}, // LongLongLongDot
2436 {3,1,1,0,0}, // LongDotDot
2437 {3,1,1,1,0}, // LongDotDotDot
2438 {3,1,3,1,0} // LongDotLongDot
2439 };
2440 if(Unit <= 0 ){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
2441 if((StdPat <= 0) || (StdPat > U_DD_LongDotLongDot26)){ return(NULL((void*)0)); }
2442 p = &(SB[StdPat][0]);
2443 for(Elements = 0; *p; p++, Elements++){}
2444 SubUnit = Unit/((U_FLOAT) Elements);
2445 Elements *= 2;
2446 p = &(SB[StdPat][0]);
2447 for(i=0; *p; p++){
2448 switch(*p){
2449 case 0: break;
2450 case 1: /* dot */
2451 Lengths[i++] = SubUnit * 0.125;
2452 Lengths[i++] = SubUnit * 0.875;
2453 break;
2454 case 2: /* dash */
2455 Lengths[i++] = SubUnit * 0.5;
2456 Lengths[i++] = SubUnit * 0.5;
2457 break;
2458 case 3: /* long */
2459 Lengths[i++] = SubUnit * 0.75;
2460 Lengths[i++] = SubUnit * 0.25;
2461 break;
2462 }
2463 }
2464
2465 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMF_DASHEDLINEDATA_set(Elements, Lengths);
2466 return(po);
2467}
2468
2469/**
2470 \brief Utility function to create and set a U_PMF_DASHEDLINEDATA PseudoObject from the bits that are set in a uint32_t
2471 \return Pointer to PseudoObject, NULL on error
2472 \param Unit Length of the repeat unit
2473 \param BitPat uint32_t holding the bit pattern, the lowest order bit MUST be set and the highest order MUST be clear.
2474
2475 Make a line with a dot/dash pattern defined by the bits in the BitPat value. If a bit is set it is drawn,
2476 if clear it is not. Every bit drawn has length Unit/32, and consecutive drawn bits are merged together.
2477 The lowest order bit is the first bit that may be drawn, the highest the last.
2478
2479 Example: if the integer has value 0x13 the pattern produced will be:
2480 0 -> 2*unit/32 drawn
2481 2*unit/32 -> 5*unit/32 not drawn
2482 5*unit/32 -> 6*unit/32 drawn
2483 6*unit/32 -> unit not drawn
2484
2485 EMF+ manual 2.2.2.16, Microsoft name: EmfPlusDashedLineData Object
2486*/
2487U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_DASHEDLINEDATA_set3(U_FLOAT Unit, uint32_t BitPat){
2488 uint32_t Elements=0;
2489 U_FLOAT SubUnit = Unit/32.0;
2490 U_FLOAT Lengths[32]; /* This is the most dash/spaces that will be needed*/
2491 if(!(0x00000001 & BitPat))return(NULL((void*)0)); /* Pattern must start with a drawn segment, this bit must be set */
2492 if( 0x80000000 & BitPat )return(NULL((void*)0)); /* Pattern must end with an undrawn segment, this bit must be clear */
2493 int i=0;
2494 int k;
2495 int lastType=1;
2496 int newType=0;
2497 uint32_t j=1;
2498 Lengths[0]=0;
2499 for(k=0; k<32; k++, j=j<<1){
2500 if(j & BitPat){
2501 if(!lastType){
2502 newType=1;
2503 }
2504 }
2505 else {
2506 if(lastType){
2507 newType=1;
2508 }
2509 }
2510 if(newType){
2511 i++;
2512 Lengths[i]=0;
2513 Elements++;
2514 lastType = !lastType;
2515 newType = 0;
2516 }
2517 Lengths[i] += SubUnit;
2518 }
2519 Elements = i+1;
2520
2521 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMF_DASHEDLINEDATA_set(Elements, Lengths);
2522 return(po);
2523}

2652/**
2653 \brief Create and set a U_PMF_LANGUAGEIDENTIFIER value in 4 byte unsigned int, in NATIVE byte order
2654 \return LID value in least significant two bytes and 0 in most significant two bytes.
2655 \param SubLId Example: code for USA
2656 \param PriLId Example: code for English
2657
2658 EMF+ manual 2.2.2.23, Microsoft name: EmfPlusLanguageIdentifier Object
2659*/
2660U_PMF_LANGUAGEIDENTIFIER U_PMF_LANGUAGEIDENTIFIEROBJ_set(int SubLId, int PriLId){
2661 U_PMF_LANGUAGEIDENTIFIER utmp32;
2662 utmp32 = ((SubLId & U_FF_MASK_SUBLID0x003F) << U_FF_SHFT_SUBLID0x000A) | ((PriLId & U_FF_MASK_PRILID0x03FF) << U_FF_SHFT_PRILID0x0000);
2663 return(utmp32);
2664}

2707/**
2708 \brief Create and set a U_PMF_LINEARGRADIENTBRUSHOPTIONALDATA PseudoObject
2709 \return Pointer to PseudoObject, NULL on error
2710 \param Flags Bits are set that indicate which of the following were included. The caller must clear before passing it in.
2711 \param Tm (optional) U_PSEUDO_OBJ containing a U_PMF_TRANSFORMMATRIX object
2712 \param Bc (optional) U_PSEUDO_OBJ containing a U_PMF_BLENDCOLORS object or NULL
2713 \param BfH (optional) U_PSEUDO_OBJ containing a U_PMF_BLENDFACTORS (H) object or NULL
2714 \param BfV (optional) U_PSEUDO_OBJ containing a U_PMF_BLENDFACTORS (V) object or NULL (WARNING, GDI+ defines this field but does not render it. DO NOT USE.)
2715
2716
2717 EMF+ manual 2.2.2.25, Microsoft name: EmfPlusLinearGradientBrushOptionalData Object
2718
2719
2720 The rectangular gradients repeat in a tiled pattern. Tm can rotate and offset the gradient within each tile.
2721 The gradient wraps when it is offset.
2722
2723*/
2724U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_LINEARGRADIENTBRUSHOPTIONALDATA_set(uint32_t *Flags, const U_PSEUDO_OBJ *Tm,
2725 const U_PSEUDO_OBJ *Bc, const U_PSEUDO_OBJ *BfH, const U_PSEUDO_OBJ *BfV){
2726 if(!Flags )return(NULL((void*)0));
2727 if(Tm && (Tm->Type != U_PMF_TRANSFORMMATRIX_OID0x02020247))return(NULL((void*)0));
2728 if(Bc && (Bc->Type != U_PMF_BLENDCOLORS_OID0x02020204) )return(NULL((void*)0));
2729 if(BfH && (BfH->Type != U_PMF_BLENDFACTORS_OID0x02020205) )return(NULL((void*)0));
2730 if(BfV && (BfV->Type != U_PMF_BLENDFACTORS_OID0x02020205) )return(NULL((void*)0));
2731 if(Bc && (BfH || BfV) )return(NULL((void*)0));
2732 const U_SERIAL_DESC List[] = {
2733 {(Tm ? Tm->Data : NULL((void*)0)), (Tm ? Tm->Used : 0), 1, U_XE0},
2734 {(Bc ? Bc->Data : NULL((void*)0)), (Bc ? Bc->Used : 0), 1, U_XE0},
2735 {(BfH ? BfH->Data : NULL((void*)0)), (BfH ? BfH->Used : 0), 1, U_XE0},
2736 {(BfV ? BfV->Data : NULL((void*)0)), (BfV ? BfV->Used : 0), 1, U_XE0},
2737 {NULL((void*)0),0,0,U_XX0xFF}
2738 };
2739 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMF_SERIAL_set(U_PMF_LINEARGRADIENTBRUSHOPTIONALDATA_OID0x02020225, List);
2740 if(Tm ){ *Flags |= U_BD_Transform0x0002; }
2741 if(Bc ){ *Flags |= U_BD_PresetColors0x0004; }
2742 if(BfH){ *Flags |= U_BD_BlendFactorsH0x0008; }
2743 if(BfV){ *Flags |= U_BD_BlendFactorsV0x0010; }
2744 return(po);
2745}

2887 \param First Apply to first point, unsigned byte, lower 4 bits hold the PathPointType flag upper 4 bits hold the PathPointType enumeration.
2888 \param Others Apply to all other points, unsigned byte, lower 4 bits hold the PathPointType flag upper 4 bits hold the PathPointType enumeration.
2889
2890 EMF+ manual 2.2.2.31, Microsoft name: EmfPlusPathPointType Object
2891*/
2892U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPE_set2(uint32_t Elements, uint8_t First, uint8_t Others){

2895 {&Elements, 4, 1, U_XE0},
2896 {&First, 1, 1, U_XE0},

2898 {NULL((void*)0),0,0,U_XX0xFF}
2899 };
2900 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PMF_SERIAL_set(U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPE_OID0x02020231 | U_PMF_ARRAY_OID0x80000000, List);

2903
2904/**
2905 \brief Create and set an ARRAY of U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPERLE objects
2906 \return Pointer to PseudoObject containing first the number of elements, then an array of U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPERLE, NULL on error
2907 \param Elements Number of entries in the arrays
2908 \param Bz Array of unsigned bytes, if not zero, element has Bezier bit set
2909 \param RL Array of unsigned bytes, Run lengths.
2910 \param Ppte Array of unsigned bytes, PathPointType enumerations.
2911
2912 EMF+ manual 2.2.2.32, Microsoft name: EmfPlusPathPointTypeRLE Object
2913*/
2914U_PSEUDO_OBJ *U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPERLE_set(uint32_t Elements, const uint8_t *Bz, const uint8_t *RL, const uint8_t *Ppte){
2915 uint8_t utmp;
2916 if(!Bz || !RL || !Ppte)return(NULL((void*)0));
2917 /* allocate space in the structure but put no data in */
2918 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *po = U_PO_create(NULL((void*)0), 4 + 2*Elements, 0, U_PMF_PATHPOINTTYPERLE_OID0x02020232 | U_PMF_ARRAY_OID0x80000000);
2919 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *holdpo = po;
2920 if(po){
2921 U_PSEUDO_OBJ *poi = U_PMF_4NUM_set(Elements);
2922 if(!poi)goto end;
2923 po = U_PO_append(po, poi->Data, poi->Used);
2924 U_PO_free(&poi);
2925 if(!po)goto end;
2926
2927 for( ;Elements; Elements--, Bz++, RL++, Ppte++){
2928 po = U_PO_append(po, (char *)Ppte, 1);
2929 if(!po)goto end;
2930
2931 if(*RL > 0x3F) goto end; /* run length too big for field */
2932
2933 utmp = (*Bz ? 1 : 0) | ((*RL & 0x3F)<<2); /* bit 1 is not used and is set to 0 */
2934 po = U_PO_append(po, (char *)&utmp, 1);
2935 if(!po)goto end;
2936 }
2937 }
2938end:
2939 if(!po)U_PO_free(&holdpo);
2940 return(holdpo);
2941}
